[4] West Africa: Germany sends motorbikes
Date: 21 Nov 2014
Source: Reliefweb (AFP) [edited]
http://reliefweb.int/report/liberia/germany-sends-motorbikes-speed-ebola-testing


The specially adapted fleet of bikes will be able to rush test samples to laboratories from remote areas, where patients can often wait 9 days or more for results. The UN's World Food Programme (WFP) said the motorbikes should cut transport delays to a day. Experts say faster test results could help slow the spread of the epidemic, which has so far claimed more than 5400 lives, according to the UN. "The samples coming from 53 districts in the 3 worst-affected countries -- Sierra Leone, Guinea and Liberia -- will be able to be taken to the closest laboratory in less than 24 hours," said WFP spokeswoman Elisabeth Byrs.

The announcement comes as a new airlift by the agency, the 5th since September [2014], landed in the Liberian capital Monrovia carrying water kits and generators. The WFP estimates that 1.7 million people in the 3 countries are threatened by hunger, 200 000 of them directly because of the Ebola outbreak.

