[5] Liberia: New focus on tracking down rural Ebola cases
Date: Fri 21 Nov 2014
Source: NPR [edited]
http://www.npr.org/2014/11/21/365638390/cdc-tries-old-school-epidemiology-to-fight-ebola


The Centers for Disease Control is trying out a system of rapid response teams for isolated rural areas. About 2 hours outside of the Liberian capital Monrovia, just down the coast on the Atlantic Ocean, near a town called Buchanan, is basically a series of tents that are the size of a house, which serve as Ebola Treatment Units (ETU), places where people can be isolated and treated who are confirmed to have the disease. But many health experts are asking whether building these Ebola Treatment Units is the best use of medical resources now in the fight against Ebola.

This is because the characteristics of the Ebola epidemic are really undergoing significant changes in Liberia. When the epidemic 1st started in Guinea and then crossed over the borders into rural Liberia, ill people started going to the capital, Monrovia, to get care. That's when there really was an explosion of cases in Monrovia. So at that time, around September 2014, health officials saw the need for treatment centers outside the main city, treatment centers in the outlying counties, so people did not need to come to the capital.

But what's happening now is people, and families are leaving the capital and going all the way back into really remote areas from which they came when they're sick. And so local hotspots occurred all over the country in very remote areas, far away even from any treatment centers.

So what a lot of experts are saying now is that there is a need to respond to this with Rapid Response Teams -- people who can get out into very remote areas to find people who are sick, or people who have been in contact with people who are sick -- and decide what to do, there, at the very local level. What began as a medical problem has now developed, in addition, into a social problem and even a political problem.

In these very remote areas, there is a major problem getting just the simplest health information message out to the populace. "Rapid" really means teaching the sort of basic public health and preventive measures that had been easier to deal with in Monrovia, with posters and public service announcements or messages on a cell phone.

The community, helped by the Rapid Response Team, might decide to just isolate the ill people there in the village and work with the community to agree who should be quarantined and treated right there in the village. They might involve a nearby village with an existing clinic, already a part of the Liberian health system. The plan might include building an isolation tent next to an existing clinic and allowing care for ill patients there. Or they might find patients and families well enough to get all the way to an existing ETU.

The ETUs are best in certain circumstances. So locations for ETUs and how best to handle rural cases are best made on a case-by-case basis. The sooner you get someone into treatment, the better chances they have of survival, because treatment is primarily hydration and medicine to take down fever... - more

[Byline: Kelly McEvers]

